1
00:00:13,160 --> 00:00:16,800
THIS PROGRAM IS THE RECORD
OF A "BATTLE" AMONGST COMEDIANS.

2
00:00:16,860 --> 00:00:19,760
IN ORDER TO PRESERVE QUALITY,
IT IS MOSTLY UNEDITED.

3
00:00:19,830 --> 00:00:22,430
AS SUCH, VIEWERS MAY ENCOUNTER
EXPLICIT CONTENT.

4
00:00:40,360 --> 00:00:43,030
-Hello, Mr. Matsumoto.
-Hello.

5
00:00:43,560 --> 00:00:47,700
As the creator of this show,
could you tell us what Documental is?

6
00:00:47,760 --> 00:00:49,000
Well...

7
00:00:49,460 --> 00:00:54,000
HITOSHI MATSUMOTO

8
00:00:54,760 --> 00:00:56,960
I had a few ideas for the title.

9
00:00:57,030 --> 00:01:00,660
But long story short,
this is a documentary of sorts.

10
00:01:00,800 --> 00:01:05,830
I wanted to focus on
the mental battle between comedians,

11
00:01:05,960 --> 00:01:08,300
so it's a "Docu-mental."

12
00:01:08,360 --> 00:01:12,460
From "documentary" and "mental"
I ended up with Documental.

13
00:01:13,430 --> 00:01:16,000
DOCUMENTAL

14
00:01:19,360 --> 00:01:23,500
What drove you to create this show
in the first place?

15
00:01:23,560 --> 00:01:25,930
Well, how should I put it?

16
00:01:26,100 --> 00:01:28,460
When you think about what I've done,

17
00:01:29,700 --> 00:01:34,130
I've devoted my whole life to comedy,
ever since I was in elementary school.

18
00:01:34,560 --> 00:01:37,030
This is the train wreck
at the end of the line.

19
00:01:37,360 --> 00:01:42,860
THIS IS HOW FAR COMEDY HAS COME

20
00:01:42,960 --> 00:01:45,460
We've all seen a variety of formats
for comedy.

21
00:01:45,530 --> 00:01:48,400
Sketches, funny stories, funny quizzes,

22
00:01:48,500 --> 00:01:51,930
duo acts, solo acts, stand-up...

23
00:01:52,000 --> 00:01:53,600
There are probably more.

24
00:01:53,700 --> 00:01:56,560
But the one format
that hasn't been done is

25
00:01:56,630 --> 00:01:58,500
a "no-holds-barred" show.

26
00:01:58,560 --> 00:02:04,100
A JOURNEY THROUGH UNCHARTED TERRITORY
"THE NO-HOLDS-BARRED SHOW"

27
00:02:04,160 --> 00:02:06,700
The comedians can do whatever they want.

28
00:02:06,930 --> 00:02:09,060
What also makes this unique is:

29
00:02:09,130 --> 00:02:13,400
Comedians usually take turns at making an
audience laugh within a given time frame.

30
00:02:13,460 --> 00:02:15,500
But on this show,

31
00:02:15,560 --> 00:02:19,060
10 comedians are confined to one room.

32
00:02:19,130 --> 00:02:22,260
They have to make the other nine laugh.

33
00:02:22,700 --> 00:02:26,230
But they have to do it
without laughing themselves.

34
00:02:26,500 --> 00:02:29,260
This might actually be the simplest way

35
00:02:29,730 --> 00:02:33,460
and the best way to decide who truly is

36
00:02:33,530 --> 00:02:35,900
the funniest person.

37
00:02:36,000 --> 00:02:39,530
THE RAWEST AND MOST DEFINITIVE BATTLE

38
00:02:40,530 --> 00:02:43,700
THE MIGHTIEST

39
00:02:43,830 --> 00:02:46,830
I must admit,
this is sort of an experiment.

40
00:02:47,300 --> 00:02:50,960
A BIG EXPERIMENT

41
00:03:00,460 --> 00:03:02,430
You scared me! Good morning.

42
00:03:03,330 --> 00:03:08,860
THE CHOSEN WARRIORS

43
00:03:09,000 --> 00:03:10,360
Mr. Oh.

44
00:03:11,860 --> 00:03:13,430
-Good morning.
-Good morning.

45
00:03:13,600 --> 00:03:15,430
-You have an invitation.
-I do?

46
00:03:17,500 --> 00:03:18,860
This is for you.

47
00:03:24,800 --> 00:03:27,200
-Here you go.
-Oh, thank you.

48
00:03:28,560 --> 00:03:29,500
Good morning.

49
00:03:30,400 --> 00:03:31,660
What is this?

50
00:03:40,130 --> 00:03:41,800
What's going on?

51
00:03:46,730 --> 00:03:48,060
Good morning.

52
00:03:48,160 --> 00:03:49,630
-Good morning.
-Good morning.

53
00:03:50,230 --> 00:03:51,400
Yes?

54
00:03:52,060 --> 00:03:52,930
This is for you.

55
00:03:55,930 --> 00:03:57,460
Does it say "Event"?

56
00:03:58,430 --> 00:04:00,200
-It says "Invitation."
-"Invita-ton"?

57
00:04:06,460 --> 00:04:07,500
Dear sirs,

58
00:04:07,660 --> 00:04:12,430
Now the autumn breeze blows,
the summer heat is but a fond memory.

59
00:04:13,030 --> 00:04:15,400
Have the seasons been treating you well?

60
00:04:15,500 --> 00:04:18,200
I send you this invitation
with my best intentions.

61
00:04:20,660 --> 00:04:25,730
I sincerely hope you will join me
with one million yen on your person.

62
00:04:26,300 --> 00:04:28,630
I am hosting a Documental.

63
00:04:30,500 --> 00:04:32,730
"With one million yen on your person"?

64
00:04:33,560 --> 00:04:34,630
One million yen?

65
00:04:34,700 --> 00:04:35,930
One million yen!

66
00:04:36,700 --> 00:04:40,130
-I have to bring one million yen?
-That's right.

67
00:04:42,500 --> 00:04:46,900
The winner will receive
a 10 million yen reward.

68
00:04:47,000 --> 00:04:49,100
To play or not, the choice is yours.

69
00:04:49,500 --> 00:04:51,130
That's too expensive!

70
00:04:52,930 --> 00:04:54,800
One million yen?

71
00:04:55,300 --> 00:04:58,160
If I win, I'll get 10 million yen.
That would be nice.

72
00:04:58,260 --> 00:05:00,060
But I don't really need it.

73
00:05:00,430 --> 00:05:02,860
More importantly,
I don't want to pay one million.

74
00:05:02,930 --> 00:05:07,530
If you don't win, you lose the entry fee?

75
00:05:08,460 --> 00:05:09,700
That's right.

76
00:05:10,500 --> 00:05:12,100
I'll have to think about it.

77
00:05:13,530 --> 00:05:15,860
If you would like to participate,

78
00:05:15,930 --> 00:05:19,300
I will inform you of the time and venue.

79
00:05:19,360 --> 00:05:21,430
I look forward to hearing from you.

80
00:05:22,030 --> 00:05:24,400
The mornings and evenings
are getting chillier.

81
00:05:25,160 --> 00:05:28,900
Please keep yourself in good health.
Yours sincerely,

82
00:05:29,860 --> 00:05:31,560
Hitoshi Matsumoto.

83
00:05:35,930 --> 00:05:37,400
No thanks.

84
00:05:38,030 --> 00:05:40,760
There's no way I could win it.

85
00:05:41,430 --> 00:05:43,800
I'd never win. No way.

86
00:05:44,060 --> 00:05:47,660
This is some grand plan devised
by the comic genius Mr. Matsumoto.

87
00:05:48,130 --> 00:05:50,960
If I just showed up,
they'd tear me to shreds.

88
00:05:53,560 --> 00:05:56,460
Hear that? The sirens are ringing already.

89
00:05:57,430 --> 00:06:02,530
This is like some new kind of scam.
You never say no to Mr. Matsumoto, right?

90
00:06:04,560 --> 00:06:07,560
There are 10 people,
and everyone brings one million.

91
00:06:07,730 --> 00:06:08,700
That's right.

92
00:06:09,000 --> 00:06:11,160
And the winner takes 10 million home...

93
00:06:16,960 --> 00:06:19,360
I think I'll laugh right away.

94
00:06:21,360 --> 00:06:22,860
I don't get it.

95
00:06:24,030 --> 00:06:25,730
What's he trying to do?

96
00:06:26,300 --> 00:06:27,100
One million yen?

97
00:06:35,260 --> 00:06:36,900
Wait. What should I do?

98
00:06:39,200 --> 00:06:41,160
This is really going to happen, right?

99
00:06:41,560 --> 00:06:43,300
-It's not a prank?
-It's not.

100
00:06:43,700 --> 00:06:45,600
Another thing is,

101
00:06:46,500 --> 00:06:50,130
I do the TV show You Mustn't Laugh
at the end of each year.

102
00:06:50,430 --> 00:06:53,060
It's become a highly entertaining show

103
00:06:53,130 --> 00:06:57,330
for all ages.

104
00:06:57,400 --> 00:06:59,760
That's great, but it can be limiting.

105
00:07:02,900 --> 00:07:05,060
THE ULTIMATE FIGHT

106
00:07:05,130 --> 00:07:08,160
I wanted to get rid of all the shackles.

107
00:07:08,300 --> 00:07:11,330
AN EXISTENTIAL WORLD OF COMEDY

108
00:07:11,760 --> 00:07:15,460
You know those moments
when you laugh the hardest?

109
00:07:15,530 --> 00:07:18,260
It may be something trivial,
but it hits your funny bone.

110
00:07:18,330 --> 00:07:23,230
I've been wanting to create something
based on that for several years.

111
00:07:23,930 --> 00:07:28,730
THIS IS THE FRONTIER OF COMEDY

112
00:07:28,800 --> 00:07:33,430
There are a tremendous number of
comedians in Japan now.

113
00:07:33,530 --> 00:07:36,830
THEY ARE THE CHOSEN BEASTS

114
00:07:37,000 --> 00:07:39,960
It's really like a jungle.

115
00:07:40,330 --> 00:07:42,660
Some comedians do well in the water.

116
00:07:42,730 --> 00:07:44,730
THEY'RE BEASTS IN THE JUNGLE

117
00:07:44,830 --> 00:07:47,330
Some just hang around in trees.

118
00:07:47,630 --> 00:07:49,100
You know what I mean?

119
00:07:49,260 --> 00:07:51,800
Some of them live in swamps.

120
00:07:52,330 --> 00:07:54,700
Some are fast runners...

121
00:07:54,760 --> 00:07:58,230
This show puts a variety of beasts
all in one room.

122
00:07:58,400 --> 00:08:00,200
THE STRONGEST IN THE WILD

123
00:08:00,260 --> 00:08:03,130
So, which of them is the strongest?

124
00:08:03,230 --> 00:08:06,700
I'm sure this won't get
high ratings on TV.

125
00:08:08,000 --> 00:08:10,860
Unless you watch pretty carefully,

126
00:08:10,930 --> 00:08:13,300
you won't grasp how funny it is.

127
00:08:13,360 --> 00:08:17,360
You could say it's aimed towards
a very specific audience.

128
00:08:18,630 --> 00:08:23,560
I wouldn't say it's a show for
older people, women, or kids.

129
00:08:23,630 --> 00:08:28,200
But I think those who like it
will be glued to the screen.

130
00:08:28,360 --> 00:08:33,100
So, I think it's not a bad idea
to narrow down our target audience.

131
00:08:33,400 --> 00:08:36,860
After all, it's not easy
to watch videos on Amazon, right?

132
00:08:37,000 --> 00:08:41,400
It's too hard for geezers, right?

133
00:08:41,700 --> 00:08:44,460
Subscribing to Amazon is too complicated
for them, right?

134
00:08:44,730 --> 00:08:46,560
Geezers can't do it.

135
00:08:46,830 --> 00:08:50,800
Early elementary kids can't do it, either.

136
00:08:51,100 --> 00:08:54,230
Those people can go elsewhere...

137
00:08:54,560 --> 00:08:55,530
Yeah.

138
00:08:55,600 --> 00:08:57,260
By the way,

139
00:08:57,330 --> 00:09:00,260
I just said comedians were like
animals in the jungle,

140
00:09:00,330 --> 00:09:03,030
and this show is on Amazon, right?

141
00:09:03,830 --> 00:09:07,000
That was either a good joke,
a little confusing, or I got it all wrong.

142
00:09:07,100 --> 00:09:08,560
I'm not sure.

143
00:10:46,360 --> 00:10:51,760
THE COMEDIANS ARRIVE AT THE BATTLEFIELD

144
00:11:10,100 --> 00:11:11,360
Am I the first one?

145
00:11:12,030 --> 00:11:13,100
I'm the first?

146
00:11:13,330 --> 00:11:14,300
Really?

147
00:11:17,400 --> 00:11:19,600
So this is the place.

148
00:11:20,700 --> 00:11:22,160
Where should I sit?

149
00:11:26,500 --> 00:11:29,560
I'm Daisuke Miyagawa. Nice to meet you.

150
00:11:31,530 --> 00:11:34,400
One million yen is a large amount.

151
00:11:36,130 --> 00:11:39,660
I had to think about it at home,
but in the end,

152
00:11:39,830 --> 00:11:41,700
it sounded like fun.

153
00:11:42,260 --> 00:11:45,160
The only problem is,
I don't have any trademark jokes.

154
00:11:45,300 --> 00:11:47,160
I don't have a killer technique.

155
00:11:47,560 --> 00:11:50,700
I don't know how I'm going to fight.

156
00:11:50,860 --> 00:11:53,830
He's an innately happy guy.

157
00:11:54,730 --> 00:11:55,700
How can I put it?

158
00:11:55,760 --> 00:11:57,830
He loves to be around people.

159
00:11:57,900 --> 00:12:01,700
He's the type of guy who always has fun,
whatever he's doing.

160
00:12:01,830 --> 00:12:03,160
HE ENJOYS WHATEVER'S
IN FRONT OF HIM

161
00:12:03,230 --> 00:12:07,860
I think he'll stir things up a lot, but...

162
00:12:09,700 --> 00:12:15,130
Unfortunately, he probably laughs the most
out of the whole group.

163
00:12:15,400 --> 00:12:18,100
QUICK TO LAUGH

164
00:12:18,160 --> 00:12:20,530
I'm scared of the guys who are weird.

165
00:12:20,600 --> 00:12:23,430
I'm not worried about any joke
or gag that's been prepared.

166
00:12:23,630 --> 00:12:26,930
But I'm scared I'll find something funny,
all by myself.

167
00:12:27,000 --> 00:12:29,260
Especially when I'm not supposed to laugh.

168
00:12:29,430 --> 00:12:33,460
I'm worried what will happen when
I start to find some trivial thing funny.

169
00:12:34,660 --> 00:12:36,700
That is his weak point.

170
00:12:36,930 --> 00:12:38,600
Do you think he can win?

171
00:12:39,300 --> 00:12:44,030
In terms of making other people laugh,
I think he does have a chance.

172
00:12:44,460 --> 00:12:46,560
It's interesting when you think about it.

173
00:12:46,630 --> 00:12:50,460
If you were to categorize his abilities
and put them in a hexagonal chart,

174
00:12:50,700 --> 00:12:54,630
he excels in one or two areas,
but, overall, it's not well-balanced.

175
00:12:56,000 --> 00:12:58,700
I don't have a strategy to be honest.

176
00:12:59,860 --> 00:13:01,230
I'll see what happens.

177
00:13:01,300 --> 00:13:03,600
It depends on the participants.

178
00:13:05,530 --> 00:13:06,730
I'll sit here.

179
00:13:09,000 --> 00:13:10,260
Wait a minute.

180
00:13:12,660 --> 00:13:14,760
Okay. I will sit here.

181
00:13:27,760 --> 00:13:29,030
Who is it?

182
00:13:41,760 --> 00:13:42,900
Excuse me.

183
00:13:46,730 --> 00:13:48,430
It's Ohchi!

184
00:13:48,800 --> 00:13:50,800
-Good morning.
-Good morning.

185
00:13:51,030 --> 00:13:54,630
I'm Yosuke Ohchi, from the duo Dienoji.
I'm 44 years old.

186
00:13:54,860 --> 00:13:57,860
I have a wife and two daughters.

187
00:13:58,060 --> 00:13:59,300
Nice to meet you.

188
00:13:59,400 --> 00:14:03,930
My wife handed me one million yen
this morning, and now I'm here.

189
00:14:04,200 --> 00:14:05,630
ASKING HIS WIFE FOR THE CASH

190
00:14:05,700 --> 00:14:07,630
Remember that one million yen I mentioned?

191
00:14:07,700 --> 00:14:08,930
Yeah, I do...

192
00:14:09,000 --> 00:14:10,900
Can I have it?

193
00:14:11,100 --> 00:14:12,560
Seriously?

194
00:14:13,600 --> 00:14:15,030
Where will I get that?

195
00:14:16,200 --> 00:14:19,200
My daughter warned me,
"Don't waste our money."

196
00:14:20,430 --> 00:14:22,160
It's Ohchi!

197
00:14:26,560 --> 00:14:27,700
You're gonna sit there?

198
00:14:27,760 --> 00:14:30,200
-Where should I sit?
-Over on the right.

199
00:14:30,300 --> 00:14:34,100
If each of them had to do something
all by themselves,

200
00:14:34,160 --> 00:14:36,530
it wouldn't be funny at all.

201
00:14:36,600 --> 00:14:40,300
Apparently, he's an air guitar champion.

202
00:14:40,360 --> 00:14:41,830
AIR GUITAR WORLD CHAMPION

203
00:14:42,160 --> 00:14:46,230
There's no way he'd win a contest like
that if he was truly a funny comedian.

204
00:14:46,400 --> 00:14:49,860
It's like showing the world
he's not funny.

205
00:14:52,100 --> 00:14:54,930
But he is a go-getter.

206
00:14:55,360 --> 00:14:58,330
It'll be fun to have one guy like him.

207
00:14:58,860 --> 00:15:04,900
However, Ohchi may be
Daisuke's Achilles' heel.

208
00:15:05,830 --> 00:15:07,860
-This is insane.
-It sure is!

209
00:15:08,500 --> 00:15:11,100
-The day has come.
-This is insane.

210
00:15:16,000 --> 00:15:18,000
-Know who's coming?
-I have no idea.

211
00:15:18,060 --> 00:15:20,060
-Nobody's said anything.
-Nothing.

212
00:15:24,530 --> 00:15:26,760
I can't believe Daisuke's here.

213
00:15:28,600 --> 00:15:29,530
Someone's coming.

214
00:15:41,200 --> 00:15:42,160
Yes?

215
00:15:42,300 --> 00:15:43,330
Hello?

216
00:15:45,430 --> 00:15:46,630
So it's you?

217
00:15:47,260 --> 00:15:48,260
Someone else from Yoshimoto.

218
00:15:48,330 --> 00:15:49,600
This guy's so annoying.

219
00:15:50,200 --> 00:15:51,560
We're all from Yoshimoto.

220
00:15:51,630 --> 00:15:52,600
Hello.

221
00:15:52,660 --> 00:15:54,330
-Nice seeing you.
-Howdy.

222
00:15:54,460 --> 00:15:57,760
I'm part of the Toro Salmon duo.
I'm Kubota. Nice to meet you.

223
00:15:58,230 --> 00:16:00,700
This guy is...

224
00:16:01,130 --> 00:16:02,630
He's a little...

225
00:16:02,960 --> 00:16:03,930
scary.

226
00:16:05,330 --> 00:16:09,930
He has a bit of a unique style of comedy.

227
00:16:10,130 --> 00:16:11,900
Seaweed. Seaweed. Seaweed.

228
00:16:11,960 --> 00:16:14,600
Is "Seaweed" a palindrome?
No, in reverse it's "Deewaes!"

229
00:16:14,660 --> 00:16:15,400
I don't get it!

230
00:16:15,560 --> 00:16:17,830
And he has what you might call...

231
00:16:18,430 --> 00:16:20,500
a psychopathic streak.

232
00:16:20,600 --> 00:16:21,900
The one million yen?

233
00:16:22,660 --> 00:16:25,160
I paid the entry fee from my savings.

234
00:16:25,260 --> 00:16:27,060
And I borrowed some.

235
00:16:27,130 --> 00:16:30,100
And I participated in a clinical trial
at a university.

236
00:16:30,800 --> 00:16:33,100
Before meds are sold at drug stores,

237
00:16:33,160 --> 00:16:36,000
they're tested out on human subjects.

238
00:16:36,330 --> 00:16:37,600
I made 200,000 yen.

239
00:16:38,930 --> 00:16:42,400
I think rich people will laugh more
because they have fewer worries.

240
00:16:44,000 --> 00:16:48,030
Poor people are defensive,
so they don't laugh much.

241
00:16:48,330 --> 00:16:51,930
To earn one million at Yoshimoto means
I could earn double that elsewhere.

242
00:16:52,160 --> 00:16:54,530
That's enough to retire on in North Korea.

243
00:16:54,600 --> 00:16:57,260
I checked the rules,
and we can use living animals.

244
00:16:57,330 --> 00:16:58,330
ANIMALS ARE PERMITTED

245
00:16:58,400 --> 00:17:01,430
I asked them to bring me
three stray dogs...

246
00:17:02,260 --> 00:17:03,500
It's Kubota...

247
00:17:03,630 --> 00:17:06,260
They're all actually quite happy people.

248
00:17:06,500 --> 00:17:08,060
Why are you wearing a tank top?

249
00:17:08,300 --> 00:17:10,200
I heard we had to wear a collared shirt.

250
00:17:10,460 --> 00:17:12,760
A collared shirt?
Did they prepare one for us?

251
00:17:12,960 --> 00:17:14,760
No, you had to bring your own.

252
00:17:15,000 --> 00:17:16,800
Why did he choose a tank top?

253
00:17:17,060 --> 00:17:20,200
I don't know if I'm hot or cold.
I've thought about this show too much.

254
00:17:20,260 --> 00:17:21,800
He looks like a rickshaw man.

255
00:17:22,100 --> 00:17:23,460
So I stripped.

256
00:17:25,860 --> 00:17:27,000
Kubota is...

257
00:17:27,700 --> 00:17:29,430
He could be dangerous.

258
00:17:30,100 --> 00:17:32,560
-We're all in danger.
-This is dangerous.

259
00:17:35,360 --> 00:17:36,360
No way.

260
00:17:36,560 --> 00:17:37,500
This is bad news.

261
00:17:38,060 --> 00:17:39,260
This is really bad.

262
00:17:42,500 --> 00:17:44,260
Fujimoto makes it a different story.

263
00:17:44,600 --> 00:17:46,100
I'm Fujimoto from Fujiwara.

264
00:17:46,960 --> 00:17:49,130
I will try my bestest!

265
00:17:49,260 --> 00:17:52,730
I simply thought it sounded like fun.

266
00:17:53,500 --> 00:17:54,530
That's all.

267
00:17:54,730 --> 00:17:57,260
In his case,

268
00:17:57,500 --> 00:18:01,560
for every single thing
anybody says or does,

269
00:18:02,100 --> 00:18:04,260
he chips in as the straight man.

270
00:18:04,330 --> 00:18:06,930
-I want your eyes to cave in!
-What the hell!

271
00:18:07,260 --> 00:18:09,100
What kind of insult is that?
"Caved-in eyes"?

272
00:18:09,160 --> 00:18:12,600
His presence could be a problem, too.

273
00:18:12,860 --> 00:18:16,900
The thing is, he plays the straight man,
but he makes funny quips, too.

274
00:18:17,000 --> 00:18:20,200
I think he may cause trouble
for the others.

275
00:18:21,230 --> 00:18:25,060
I'll just deal with whatever unfolds.

276
00:18:25,860 --> 00:18:27,630
That's my only plan.

277
00:18:27,860 --> 00:18:28,630
Yeah.

278
00:18:28,700 --> 00:18:32,630
If Ohchi does something silly,
and Fujimoto starts to play with that,

279
00:18:32,700 --> 00:18:35,030
it will be tough for the others.

280
00:18:35,630 --> 00:18:37,160
My wife said,

281
00:18:38,130 --> 00:18:40,060
"You wanna be on the show, right?

282
00:18:40,660 --> 00:18:42,100
Then go for it."

283
00:18:42,930 --> 00:18:44,600
She was supportive.

284
00:18:44,760 --> 00:18:46,400
And she's the breadwinner anyway.

285
00:18:46,500 --> 00:18:48,300
In fact, it's like...

286
00:18:48,660 --> 00:18:50,530
I can hear a little devil saying,

287
00:18:50,630 --> 00:18:52,830
"It's okay to laugh and lose.
Your wife is rich!"

288
00:18:53,630 --> 00:18:54,600
Right here.

289
00:18:54,700 --> 00:18:56,700
-Is that all you brought?
-Yeah.

290
00:18:57,460 --> 00:18:58,700
How much did you bring?

291
00:18:59,060 --> 00:19:00,430
That's what I brought.

292
00:19:00,630 --> 00:19:02,700
-What did he bring?
-A pouch.

293
00:19:02,800 --> 00:19:05,230
RULE 1: YOU MAY BRING PROPS

294
00:19:05,430 --> 00:19:07,830
-Is that all?
-Your bag is huge!

295
00:19:07,930 --> 00:19:10,560
-You're gonna make us laugh that much?
-No, that's not why...

296
00:19:10,630 --> 00:19:13,060
-What's inside that?
-Isn't that too small?

297
00:19:13,330 --> 00:19:15,260
-What's in it?
-Well...

298
00:19:15,800 --> 00:19:18,500
That's not a bag people take to work.

299
00:19:18,900 --> 00:19:20,630
But, it's...

300
00:19:20,730 --> 00:19:23,960
And this is what it's like
with only four people.

301
00:19:24,700 --> 00:19:26,330
You're not scared of me.

302
00:19:27,000 --> 00:19:29,130
-I didn't expect Daisuke to be here.
-Right?

303
00:19:29,200 --> 00:19:32,330
-I didn't think so, either.
-I thought you were abroad.

304
00:19:32,560 --> 00:19:33,800
I get that a lot.

305
00:19:33,960 --> 00:19:36,260
-You should stay there.
-What does that mean?

306
00:19:36,930 --> 00:19:39,930
Doing overseas reports and eating.
Those jobs suit you.

307
00:19:40,500 --> 00:19:43,330
-What's your problem?
-Go overseas, or to the countryside.

308
00:19:43,930 --> 00:19:45,560
-Look. It's him.
-Uh-oh.

309
00:19:46,500 --> 00:19:47,530
The monster's here.

310
00:19:47,660 --> 00:19:49,230
It's turning into a heavy-weight match.

311
00:19:50,000 --> 00:19:51,600
A monster has arrived.

312
00:19:52,460 --> 00:19:54,060
For real?

313
00:19:55,430 --> 00:19:57,400
I'm Kukky, from Yaseibakudan.

314
00:19:57,660 --> 00:20:00,060
The reason I became a comedian was

315
00:20:00,660 --> 00:20:03,100
I wanted to steal money from
the general public.

316
00:20:03,330 --> 00:20:05,730
I never thought someone would steal
from me.

317
00:20:05,800 --> 00:20:06,700
I said,

318
00:20:06,800 --> 00:20:09,660
"Dude, can you lend me a million yen?"

319
00:20:09,800 --> 00:20:12,900
I borrowed the money from a place called
Yoshimoto Finance.

320
00:20:13,260 --> 00:20:14,500
I signed a lot of papers.

321
00:20:14,630 --> 00:20:16,630
They gave me the loan without any hassle.

322
00:20:16,760 --> 00:20:17,960
It's a very nice company.

323
00:20:18,100 --> 00:20:20,200
The payments get taken out of my salary.

324
00:20:20,260 --> 00:20:21,700
A MILLION YEN LOAN FROM YOSHIMOTO

325
00:20:21,760 --> 00:20:24,330
-I have to pay back 100,000 yen a month?
-Yes.

326
00:20:24,800 --> 00:20:30,400
Well, he is even more of a psychopath.

327
00:20:31,000 --> 00:20:33,160
YET ANOTHER PSYCHOPATH

328
00:20:33,530 --> 00:20:35,360
He has a butterfly knife?

329
00:20:36,560 --> 00:20:40,630
If he sets up some kind of trap,

330
00:20:41,200 --> 00:20:43,300
they'll be in trouble indeed.

331
00:20:43,960 --> 00:20:45,700
He's a war veteran!

332
00:20:45,760 --> 00:20:48,600
-Is that a tent?
-Look at Fujimoto's small bag.

333
00:20:49,230 --> 00:20:50,830
I brought 18 robot model kits.

334
00:20:56,160 --> 00:20:57,400
That was a forced punchline.

335
00:20:57,460 --> 00:21:00,600
I think he will do pretty well.

336
00:21:00,900 --> 00:21:04,300
Every time he does something
that seems random,

337
00:21:04,360 --> 00:21:06,760
you start to imagine
what led him to do it.

338
00:21:07,160 --> 00:21:09,760
He can be incredibly funny.

339
00:21:10,460 --> 00:21:11,630
I'll laugh.

340
00:21:12,360 --> 00:21:13,830
I'm already laughing. See?

341
00:21:13,960 --> 00:21:15,760
That's the type of guy I am.

342
00:21:16,000 --> 00:21:18,060
I even laugh at my own jokes.

343
00:21:18,230 --> 00:21:19,300
I'm in trouble.

344
00:21:19,360 --> 00:21:23,600
I'm like canned laughter.
Call me "Can-ghter"

345
00:21:23,860 --> 00:21:26,700
-He means trouble.
-For real? Damn it.

346
00:21:26,860 --> 00:21:29,160
Just make him laugh first.

347
00:21:29,560 --> 00:21:30,430
I'm in trouble.

348
00:21:30,900 --> 00:21:33,200
-These guys crack me up.
-I have a bad feeling.

349
00:21:34,600 --> 00:21:37,530
-I don't like this...
-It feels like we're backstage at Lumine.

350
00:21:37,600 --> 00:21:38,860
Here's another one.

351
00:21:39,730 --> 00:21:41,500
-We got another one.
-I'm done for.

352
00:21:43,460 --> 00:21:45,330
That's the face you'd expect.

353
00:21:46,030 --> 00:21:47,630
-It's him.
-Another dangerous one.

354
00:21:47,900 --> 00:21:49,930
Hi. I am from Japan.

355
00:21:50,460 --> 00:21:51,530
I'm from Trendy Angel.

356
00:21:52,500 --> 00:21:55,000
I think my name is Saito.
Nice to meet you.

357
00:21:55,400 --> 00:21:58,030
I'm this year's "Biggest Hit Comedian."

358
00:21:59,060 --> 00:22:01,630
I've starred in 11 commercials this year.

359
00:22:02,600 --> 00:22:04,930
But I only have 700,000 yen in my account.

360
00:22:11,030 --> 00:22:14,660
I think Saito is the most well-balanced
out of this group.

361
00:22:15,230 --> 00:22:16,560
In many respects.

362
00:22:17,260 --> 00:22:20,560
-He always makes me laugh.
-Stay over there. Next to Ohchi.

363
00:22:21,000 --> 00:22:22,560
-Don't come here.
-Don't say that--

364
00:22:22,630 --> 00:22:24,730
-Oops!
-We haven't started yet.

365
00:22:24,800 --> 00:22:29,700
There are many disadvantages for Saito.

366
00:22:30,700 --> 00:22:33,900
The other nine will never laugh.

367
00:22:34,600 --> 00:22:37,260
at his bald head.

368
00:22:37,830 --> 00:22:38,930
HIS BALDNESS IS LAME

369
00:22:39,000 --> 00:22:40,530
That's a key point.

370
00:22:40,600 --> 00:22:44,530
Women and children might find it funny,
but being bald won't cut it here.

371
00:22:44,860 --> 00:22:47,000
There's no way I'll lose.

372
00:22:48,900 --> 00:22:50,930
-How big is his bag?
-Show us.

373
00:22:51,000 --> 00:22:52,700
-This is it.
-Are you kidding?

374
00:22:52,760 --> 00:22:54,930
-Is that all?
-Look at Fujimoto's.

375
00:22:56,430 --> 00:22:57,830
That's too small.

376
00:22:57,960 --> 00:23:00,500
-What's with that pouch?
-That's your weapon?

377
00:23:00,560 --> 00:23:02,660
New shoes come in bags like that.

378
00:23:02,730 --> 00:23:06,600
Everyone's really happy and smiling now.

379
00:23:06,900 --> 00:23:09,300
The atmosphere's nice and relaxed, but...

380
00:23:10,000 --> 00:23:13,130
For now, they can enjoy themselves,
but soon...

381
00:23:14,100 --> 00:23:16,960
-That's just wrong.
-I was told to wear a collared shirt.

382
00:23:17,030 --> 00:23:19,500
-Then you need a collar.
-Mine has one.

383
00:23:23,760 --> 00:23:26,060
Here's another twisted one.

384
00:23:26,700 --> 00:23:27,800
Too many weirdos.

385
00:23:27,860 --> 00:23:30,130
He's twisted and knotted.

386
00:23:30,200 --> 00:23:32,660
I'm Tenjikunezumi's Kawahara.

387
00:23:32,960 --> 00:23:34,400
I'm looking forward to it.

388
00:23:34,500 --> 00:23:37,230
I went home to think about this properly.

389
00:23:37,300 --> 00:23:39,600
I tried to figure it out.

390
00:23:39,660 --> 00:23:42,300
But even then, I couldn't really get it.

391
00:23:42,500 --> 00:23:44,660
And now, I still don't get it.

392
00:23:44,730 --> 00:23:47,930
He's got peculiarities.

393
00:23:48,930 --> 00:23:50,760
I hope they're not my juniors.

394
00:23:50,860 --> 00:23:52,460
If they're my seniors,

395
00:23:52,830 --> 00:23:55,630
I can give them all I've got.

396
00:23:56,200 --> 00:23:58,400
-We're done for.
-He never shows any emotion.

397
00:23:58,460 --> 00:24:00,830
-Kawahara never laughs.
-You're right.

398
00:24:00,900 --> 00:24:02,030
He's a tough opponent.

399
00:24:02,100 --> 00:24:05,530
He's not the type to pull
a lot of punches.

400
00:24:06,460 --> 00:24:11,160
I don't think he will be dismissed
in the first half.

401
00:24:11,530 --> 00:24:12,960
I can't picture him splitting his sides

402
00:24:13,030 --> 00:24:17,600
with laughter at something somebody does.

403
00:24:18,000 --> 00:24:20,800
Every now and then you'll find
a comedian like that.

404
00:24:21,030 --> 00:24:22,330
Like Itsuji Itao.

405
00:24:22,560 --> 00:24:24,500
THE "ITSUJI ITAO TYPE"

406
00:24:26,000 --> 00:24:27,830
I would like 10 million yen.

407
00:24:27,900 --> 00:24:30,730
But more than that,
I want to leave my mark.

408
00:24:30,860 --> 00:24:35,200
I want to leave a mark worth
one million yen.

409
00:24:37,130 --> 00:24:38,960
You brought enough for a camp.

410
00:24:39,130 --> 00:24:41,900
-All I brought was one big sausage.
-That bombed.

411
00:24:43,100 --> 00:24:47,100
-That bombed as much as your 18 robots.
-No, mine's funnier than a sausage.

412
00:24:50,230 --> 00:24:51,860
He's incredibly expressionless.

413
00:24:51,930 --> 00:24:52,900
Good morning.

414
00:24:56,960 --> 00:24:58,700
I'm Jiro Hachimitsu.

415
00:24:58,800 --> 00:25:03,100
I'll try to take myself into
a state of emptiness.

416
00:25:03,660 --> 00:25:05,200
As empty as possible.

417
00:25:05,760 --> 00:25:07,800
-Good morning.
-I've never seen him laugh.

418
00:25:07,860 --> 00:25:09,800
-He never laughs.
-He does, but...

419
00:25:09,860 --> 00:25:12,200
Yeah, he's not really the type to laugh.

420
00:25:12,330 --> 00:25:16,000
Simply put,
his comedic aptitude is very high.

421
00:25:16,130 --> 00:25:18,600
MR. HIGHLY PROFICIENT

422
00:25:19,360 --> 00:25:22,560
Don't talk about Thomas and Friends now.
There's a subway below us.

423
00:25:22,630 --> 00:25:26,230
He's a straight man who makes funny quips,
but he's different from Fujimoto.

424
00:25:26,300 --> 00:25:29,700
Whenever something happens,
he'll quietly mutter a witty remark.

425
00:25:29,760 --> 00:25:32,730
That's what slowly creeps up on you.

426
00:25:33,130 --> 00:25:34,660
He is a strong opponent.

427
00:25:35,430 --> 00:25:38,600
I was honored.
I accepted the offer right away.

428
00:25:38,730 --> 00:25:42,560
The biggest problem was,
I didn't have a million yen.

429
00:25:42,960 --> 00:25:47,560
My motto is, "Money is not something
you keep overnight."

430
00:25:47,930 --> 00:25:51,460
I have a lot of confidence,
but at the same time,

431
00:25:52,000 --> 00:25:55,600
I laugh easily at the corniest jokes.

432
00:25:56,000 --> 00:25:56,860
I'm in the middle?

433
00:25:56,930 --> 00:25:59,400
Has anyone ever seen Jiro laugh out loud?

434
00:25:59,460 --> 00:26:00,760
-No.
-Never.

435
00:26:01,230 --> 00:26:02,560
All he does is smile.

436
00:26:02,730 --> 00:26:06,260
Now that you mention it,
I've never seen him roll in laughter.

437
00:26:06,360 --> 00:26:08,460
-I laugh at Mr. Bean.
-Mr. Bean?

438
00:26:08,800 --> 00:26:11,300
-Only Mr. Bean?
-Stop trying to make us laugh.

439
00:26:11,600 --> 00:26:14,200
This is an amazing group.

440
00:26:18,430 --> 00:26:19,960
Is it a female contestant?

441
00:26:21,960 --> 00:26:23,630
It's "Thony-An."

442
00:26:24,200 --> 00:26:26,260
We're all from Yoshimoto.

443
00:26:27,860 --> 00:26:29,060
Hello...

444
00:26:30,730 --> 00:26:33,860
Hello. I'm Anthony from the Matenrou duo.

445
00:26:35,130 --> 00:26:38,430
Right now, I'm full of dread.

446
00:26:38,930 --> 00:26:40,800
And this guy...

447
00:26:42,230 --> 00:26:46,030
I think his career is a lot shorter
than the others.

448
00:26:46,130 --> 00:26:49,630
If he doesn't hold back
in front of his seniors,

449
00:26:49,730 --> 00:26:52,400
he might do well...

450
00:26:52,500 --> 00:26:54,360
But, Anthony?

451
00:26:54,730 --> 00:26:58,030
I think he might hold back a little
out of respect for his seniors.

452
00:26:58,200 --> 00:27:00,300
Last month I earned 220,000 yen.

453
00:27:00,400 --> 00:27:03,560
I borrowed 500,000 yen
from my senior colleagues.

454
00:27:04,900 --> 00:27:06,760
Thank you so much, BKB.

455
00:27:06,900 --> 00:27:09,130
I don't want to regret lending you this.

456
00:27:09,200 --> 00:27:12,030
Make me glad that I lent it to you.

457
00:27:12,130 --> 00:27:13,630
-Certainly.
-Keep that in mind.

458
00:27:14,600 --> 00:27:16,600
-I'm sure you have the money.
-I don't.

459
00:27:16,960 --> 00:27:18,130
Stop acting poor.

460
00:27:18,800 --> 00:27:20,630
Thank you for lending me the money.

461
00:27:21,360 --> 00:27:24,660
I borrowed from my mom as well,
and I finally raised one million.

462
00:27:25,130 --> 00:27:28,730
He's the only one not fully Japanese,
so it'll be interesting.

463
00:27:31,830 --> 00:27:35,660
But when it comes to these guys,
it's like what I said about Saito.

464
00:27:36,630 --> 00:27:40,400
They won't laugh at his usual jokes.
Not when he only looks a bit different.

465
00:27:41,230 --> 00:27:44,930
When I first got to quit my part-time job
after becoming a comedian,

466
00:27:45,530 --> 00:27:47,800
I was so happy.

467
00:27:47,930 --> 00:27:50,560
I never want to have
a part-time job again.

468
00:27:51,160 --> 00:27:53,760
But if I lose this,
I'll have to find a part-time job.

469
00:27:55,200 --> 00:27:56,530
You look like a backpacker.

470
00:27:58,630 --> 00:27:59,860
Where'd he come from?

471
00:28:00,160 --> 00:28:03,760
-Stop making funny quips.
-Why? We haven't started yet.

472
00:28:04,960 --> 00:28:06,400
He looks like a hitchhiker.

473
00:28:06,900 --> 00:28:08,530
So there are nine.

474
00:28:08,630 --> 00:28:11,030
We have nine participants now.

475
00:28:11,560 --> 00:28:14,360
That means there's one more.

476
00:28:15,160 --> 00:28:16,600
One more.

477
00:28:17,960 --> 00:28:19,800
Who is the last participant?

478
00:28:25,860 --> 00:28:27,660
I'm sure it's someone from Yoshimoto.

479
00:28:30,400 --> 00:28:32,200
-No way.
-The worst participant!

480
00:28:33,400 --> 00:28:35,830
-Oh, no!
-This is terrible!

481
00:28:37,760 --> 00:28:38,900
I'm Jimmy Onishi.

482
00:28:39,330 --> 00:28:41,530
I'm just going to try my best.

483
00:28:41,700 --> 00:28:43,860
He is a monster.

484
00:28:46,430 --> 00:28:50,160
The nine others are not going to like it.

485
00:28:51,460 --> 00:28:53,000
Not with him here.

486
00:28:53,560 --> 00:28:55,900
The consumer loan officer told me
I can't borrow a million yen.

487
00:28:56,760 --> 00:28:58,930
Because my annual income is only
six million.

488
00:28:59,030 --> 00:29:04,830
It really hit me how low
my standing is in society.

489
00:29:05,360 --> 00:29:06,630
He laughs easily.

490
00:29:09,800 --> 00:29:13,260
All it would take is one
really simple dirty joke.

491
00:29:13,500 --> 00:29:14,860
He's that stupid.

492
00:29:15,160 --> 00:29:17,600
Well, you see...

493
00:29:17,660 --> 00:29:20,730
Dumb luck always plays a part in comedy.

494
00:29:20,800 --> 00:29:22,730
I'm going to aim for dumb luck.

495
00:29:23,660 --> 00:29:24,830
He's already won.

496
00:29:24,930 --> 00:29:26,260
Look how grey his hair is.

497
00:29:27,160 --> 00:29:29,060
-Stop saying things like that.
-Why?

498
00:29:29,160 --> 00:29:30,330
Stop it.

499
00:29:30,430 --> 00:29:33,430
This is really going to be something.

500
00:29:55,760 --> 00:29:59,360
They are quite an elite troop.

501
00:29:59,600 --> 00:30:01,760
THE ELITE TROOP

502
00:30:01,860 --> 00:30:03,800
I think this will be great.

503
00:30:05,100 --> 00:30:06,130
This is not good.

504
00:30:06,200 --> 00:30:09,060
-With him here...
-Jimmy is too much.

505
00:30:09,130 --> 00:30:12,360
It might be over before we use
any of our props.

506
00:30:14,760 --> 00:30:16,530
Are you laughing because he's black?

507
00:30:16,830 --> 00:30:18,460
That's wrong.

508
00:30:19,500 --> 00:30:20,760
What's so funny?

509
00:30:22,360 --> 00:30:23,430
